  <ul class="media-grid">
    <li>
      <img class="thumbnail header" src="/images/blog/boards/header.png" alt="Building your house hub">
    </li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>
    Have you ever wished to make your house accessible from the web? 
    In the <a href="/blog/electronics/">previous article</a> we pointed out the existing 
    solutions to hack a device with boards like Arduino or Nanode. Anyway those solutions 
    are not (yet) powerful enough to build a secure home automation hub.
  </p>

  <p>
    <!--We wrote an <a href="/blog/access/">article talking about this</a>.-->
    Now it's time to find out more powerful solutions to build an home automation hub which 
    let all of your devices communicate with the web.
  </p>

  <h3><a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org/">Raspberry PI</a></h3>

  <p>
    This is probably the best solution out there. It's a real computer where you can run 
    Debian Linux at only $25. The initiative, started at Cambridge University got lot of 
    attention from all media around the world and in 4 months they were able to sell over
    500.000 pieces.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Raspberry PI | $25 <br/>
          Raspberry Model B | $35 <br/>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Debian Linux. <a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads">See other distributions</a>.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          The base version does not offer connectivity.<br/>
          Raspberry Model B</a> gives you an Ethernet access.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Low price, community, documentation, open-source.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Computational power, wireless connectivity.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://www.rikomagic.co.uk/">Rikomagic MK802</a></h3>

  <p>
    A fully functional computer no bigger than a USB pen drive, the Rikomagic MK802 runs on 
    the popular Android 4 operating system and it features Wifi. The design is just cool and 
    you have a fully functional computer no bigger than a USB pen drive.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          MK802 | $74
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Android 4.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Wifi 802.11b/g/n.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Low price, wireless connectivity, design.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Missing community, documentation, computational power.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://liliputing.com/2012/03/mele-a1000-is-a-70-hackable-linux-friendly-arm-based-pc.html">Mele A1000</a></h3>

  <p>
    Available for as little as $70, while that's twice the price of a Raspberry Pi computer, 
    the Mele A1000 includes a faster processor, more RAM and a case. It can be a better choice
    if the power given by the Raspberry PI is not enough and you need something aesthetically 
    nice.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Mele A1000 | $70
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Android and Ubuntu.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Ethernet by default.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Low price.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Missing community, wireless connectivity, computational power.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://beagleboard.org/">BeagleBoard</a></h3>

  <p>
    The BeagleBoard is a low cost, high performance, low power 
    <a href="http://www.ti.com/omapwireless">OMAP3</a> based platform designed 
    by BeagleBoard.org community members. It is open-source and there are hundreds of
    applications developed on top of it.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          BeagleBone | $89 <br/>
          BeagleBoard xM | $149 
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Android, and major Linux distributions like Ubuntu, Debian, ArchLinux and Gentoo. 
          <a href="http://pandaboard.org/content/resources/software">See supported distributions</a>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Ethernet by default.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Experience, community, documentation, computational power, open-source.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Price, wireless connectivity.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://pandaboard.org//">PandaBoard ES</a></h3>

  <p>
    PandaBoard is a low-cost, open <a href="http://www.ti.com/omapwireless">OMAP 4</a> mobile 
    software development platform.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          PandaBoard ES | $189
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Android, Ubuntu and Linaro.
          <a href="http://pandaboard.org/content/resources/software">See supported distributions</a>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Ethernet connectivity and Wifi 802.11 b/g/n.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Community, computational power, wireless connectivity, focus on mobile.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Price.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://www.plugcomputer.org/">Plug Computers (Sheevaplug)</a></h3>

  <p>
    Main resource for the plug computer development community. Plugcomputer.org
    offers solutions built on a Marvell system-on-chip and focus on high performances and giving
    full connected devices readily available for developers.
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          GuruPlug Display | $199 <br/>
          D2Plug | $249
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>OS</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Ubuntu, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Windows CE and any other operating system that is compatible 
          with ARM CPUs.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Connectivity</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Ethernet connectivity by default.
          Model D2Plug offers integrated 802.11 b/g/n Wifi.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Pros</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Commercial support, computational power, design, wireless connectivity.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Cons</span>
        </td>
        <td>
          Missing community, closed-source, price.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3><a href="http://www.ionicsplug.com/">Ionics Plug</a></h3>

  <p>
    Plug computer with main focus on connectivity and low price. Ionics, comes from the same
    family of Sheevaplug computers, but with lower prices and better features. For sure one 
    of the best solutions whenever you want to use a Plug Computer and you are searching for
    advanced wireless capabilities (WifI, Zigbee and Z-Wave ).
  </p>

  <table class="zebra-striped">
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="parameter">
          <span>Price</span>
        </td>
